      كُسْبُرَةٌ and كُسْبَرَةٌ The plant of the جُلْجُلَان;
(K;) [i. e., the plant of which the fruit, or produce, is called الجُلْجُلَان;] dial. forms of كُزْبُرَةٌ
and كُزْبَرَةٌ, q. v. (TA.)


      مُنْكَسِرٌ has for its pl. مَكَاسِيرُ, which is extr.;
like مَسَاحِيقُ, pl. of مُنْسَحِقٌ. (TA in art. سحق.)
رَأَيْتُهُ مُنْكَسِرًا (tropical:)  I saw him in a languid, or languishing state. (A.)


      بَلَآءٌ مُكْلِحٌ A trial, or an affliction, which, by
its severity, makes men grin and frown. (L,
from a trad.)


      مُكْنِبٌ and ↓ مِكْنَبٌ A coarse, or rough, hoof;
(IAar, K;) and the same words, and ↓ مُكْنَبٌ, the
same as applied to a camel's foot. (IAar)


      كَنْثَبٌ and كُنْثُبٌ and كُنَاثِبٌ Hard and
strong: (K:) but the ث in this case is corrupted
from ت: see كُنْتُبٌ in art. كنب. (TA.)


      كَنْعَدٌ A kind of sea-fish; (S, L, K;) as also
كَنْعَتٌ, in which the ت seems to be a substitute
for the د. (L.)


      كَهْدٌ Distress; trouble; fatigue; weariness;
i. q. جَهْدٌ. (TA.) You say أَصَابَهُ جَهْدٌ وَكَهْدٌ
[Distress, &c., befell him]. (L, K.)


      4 
      اكاحهُ He destroyed him. (T, in this art;
and K in art. كيح.) See 1.
